# {title}

A side panel shows a **live JSON export** of the alignment â€” the same structured data
the app exists to produce, rendered as syntax-highlighted, column-aligned JSON that
updates as the user works. Three pieces make this up: the export *data*, the
*formatter*, and the *panel*.

## The export data

The export is a `$derived` value on `Alignment`, shaped as a
[[data-and-tokenization/tokens|`QuoteExport`]]:

```ts
{
  meta:        { sourceText, targetText, authorship },  // sanitised
  sourceTokens, targetTokens,                            // the live token arrays
  mappings,                                              // colorIndex stripped (ExportMapping)
}
```

Two deliberate transforms happen on the way out:

- **`meta` text is sanitised.** The textareas can contain newlines, which shouldn't
  leak into the exported metadata. `sourceText` has newlines removed entirely (Han
  text has no inter-word spaces anyway); `targetText` and `authorship` collapse
  newline runs to a single space and trim the result.
- **`colorIndex` is dropped** from each mapping â€” color is a presentation concern, not
  part of the alignment data. See [[data-and-tokenization/mapping#what-gets-exported]].

## The formatter

A recursive pretty-printer produces output that's *almost* standard
`JSON.stringify(v, null, 2)`, with two differences chosen to make the result more
readable for this specific shape of data:

1. **Arrays of primitives stay on one line** â€” `"sourceTokenIds": [0, 1]` rather than
   one element per line, so ID lists don't dominate the output vertically.
2. **Arrays of token objects render as a column-aligned table.** A token is recognised
   by its shape (`id`, `text`, `line`, `type`, all primitive-valued), and each field is
   padded to the widest value across the array so the same field lines up in the same
   column on every row:

   ```
   { "id": 0, "text": "çźĄ", "pinyin": "zhÄ«",  "line": 0, "type": "character" }
   { "id": 1, "text": "ĺ‘˝", "pinyin": "mĂ¬ng", "line": 0, "type": "character" }
   ```

   The `pinyin` column is omitted entirely when no token in the array carries one â€”
   e.g. target tokens never have pinyin, so that array never gets a pinyin column.

`undefined` values render as the literal text `undefined` â€” not valid JSON, but
intentional: it makes an un-annotated source character's pinyin visible in the export
rather than silently absent. See
[[data-and-tokenization/tokens#why-pinyin-has-three-states]].

This formatter has no component dependencies, so its rules (one-lining primitives, the
literal `undefined`, column alignment and omission) are unit-tested directly.

## The panel

The export panel takes the formatted text and feeds it to a generic Shiki-based syntax
highlighter.

### Recoloring to the app's palette

By default, a Shiki-highlighted JSON block would look like a generic code preview â€”
whichever colors the highlighting theme happens to use. To make the export feel like
part of the app rather than a code snippet pasted in, the highlighter accepts a color
replacement map applied on top of its base theme:

| Role | Replaced with |
|------|-----------------|
| strings | a palette color |
| properties / colons / brackets | a flat neutral gray |
| numbers | a different palette color |
| the `undefined` literal | a third palette color |

This is why [[data-and-tokenization/tokens#colors|the color module]] exports a
name-keyed lookup alongside the index-keyed palette array â€” this recolor wants
*specific* named entries, not "the Nth mapping color".

> **Fragility:** this works by matching literal hex strings from the highlighter's base
> theme. If that theme's palette ever changes upstream, these replacements would
> silently stop matching and the export would revert to the theme's original colors.

### Rendering details

The highlighter is lazy-loaded and re-tokenizes on every change to the export text. The
output box grows to fit its widest line (rather than wrapping), which matters because
the panel's padding needs to sit *past* the longest line, not behind it, once the
content is wide enough to need horizontal scrolling.

For where this panel appears on screen at different viewport sizes â€” a side panel vs.
the slide-in modal â€” see [[components/layout]].
